  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 11:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἐν ταύτῃ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in faith, i.e. by faith",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the following verses: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κατὰ πίστιν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "according to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "faith;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "διὰ πίστιν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "through faith",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 11:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 11:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γὰρ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Paul shows the nature of faith from the examples of men in the times of old. Many things, which they hoped for and did not see, subsequently came to pass and were conspicuously seen, the event confirming faith.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐμαρτυρήθησαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "obtained a good report",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") This word is very full of meaning. GOD not only gave His testimony ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "concerning them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but also partly ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". They RECEIVED THE TESTIMONY, an equivalent to the things themselves; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 11:4-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 11:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". From this circumstance, they also became ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "witnesses;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " so that they themselves ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "might testify",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to others, and that others ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "might testify",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " concerning them; ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 12:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οἱ πρεσβύτεροι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the elders",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", who lived both formerly and for a long time. He does not say, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οἱ ἀρχαῖοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ancients",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the elders",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as it were by personification, inasmuch as they still give their powerful testimony, as if they were present; comp. ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 12:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is an excellent summary of the Old Testament, in which the apostle, by a remarkable gradation, comprehends the pursuits of those men of former times—their labours, journeyings, expectations, temptations, martyrdoms; and shows how we ought to seek, in all its fulness, under the veil of history, the substance of doctrine sometimes briefly indicated. Those of them who were earlier, had the exercise of their patience most chiefly during a long period of life; those who were later, in the midst of sharper afflictions.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For in this",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e. faith",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐν ταύτῃ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the elders obtained a good report",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; literally ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "were witnessed of",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it was in respect of their faith, which inspired their deeds, that they were praised. (For a similar use of the preposition ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 11:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐπαινέσω ἐν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τούτῳ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Thus is introduced the illustrative review of Old Testament instances, the purpose of which has been explained above. It begins from the beginning, Abel being the first example. But in the Old Testament the account of the creation precedes that first recorded instance; and, therefore, it is in the first place fittingly referred to, the existence of an unseen creative power mentally perceived beyond things visible, being the primary article - the very foundation - of all religious faith (cf. below, ver. 6). Hebrews 11:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For by it (ἐν ταύτῃ γὰρ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit. for in this. Rend. therein: in the sphere and exercise of faith: as believers. Comp. 1 Timothy 5:10. For introduces a proof of the preceding statement concerning the nature of faith. Faith has power to see and realize the unseen, for the experience of the fathers proves it.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Lit. for in this. Rend. therein: in the sphere and exercise of faith: as believers. Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Timothy 5:10",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". For introduces a proof of the preceding statement concerning the nature of faith. Faith has power to see and realize the unseen, for the experience of the fathers proves it.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The elders obtained a good report (ἐμαρτυρηθήσαν οἱ πρεσβύτεροι)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The elders for the more common the fathers: the saints of the O.T. dispensation, many of whose names are recorded in this chapter. Εμαρτυρηθήσαν, lit. were borne witness to. God bore witness to them in the victory of their faith over all obstacles, and their characters and deeds as men of faith were recorded in Scripture. For this use of ματυρεῖν in the passive, see Acts 6:3; Acts 10:22; Acts 16:12; Romans 3:21; Hebrews 7:8, Hebrews 7:17. Notice that the statement in this verse does not begin the list of examples, which commences with Hebrews 11:4, but is closely attached to the definition in Hebrews 11:1 as a comprehensive justification of it. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The elders for the more common the fathers: the saints of the O.T. dispensation, many of whose names are recorded in this chapter. Εμαρτυρηθήσαν, lit. were borne witness to. God bore witness to them in the victory of their faith over all obstacles, and their characters and deeds as men of faith were recorded in Scripture. For this use of ματυρεῖν in the passive, see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 6:3",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
